metadata.name: Universal Rayhatcher #313
metadata.description:
# What is this?

This is 6942 characters of highly experimental code.

This is a version of my rayhatcher framework (see https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/rayhatching-evolution) that can do literally everything. Or, at least anything you can do within 512 characters of Javascript code. Which is slightly more than a mortal brain can comprehend.

This is my answer to the question: What is the least restrictive set of parameters for fx(params)?

# Should I be minting this?

Depends if you know and like building SDF formulas. Otherwise probably not. Like I said, this is highly experimental code. But it's definitely worth checking the collection and/or secondary for cool stuff that is already minted.

# How does it work?

The minter designs an SDF (Signed Distance Function) which is rendered using my rayhatcher algorithm. They then use the SDF formula in the SDF Code parameter. It's not very complicated, just efficient.

You can press "h" to load the documentation and read about how everything works. Or you can press "d" to read the dev docs. 

# Anything else?

Don't forget that the "Title Seed" param also becomes the "Title" feature of the mint, so make it count.

The params, including the SDF code actually get saved on-chain. Even better, all params and the entire code required to reproduce the image are included in the SVG when saved. See https://twitter.com/piterpasma/status/1649071912742420482 .

Shortcuts are an invitation to embrace the uncharted, to question established norms, and to embark on a voyage of discovery. They remind us that the journey itself holds immeasurable value, challenging us to reconsider possibilities and find our true selves along the way.

metadata.name: Skravert #9
metadata.description:
‘Skravert’ - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‘The act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area’.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021

metadata.name: Cuts #40
metadata.description:
Cuts is an abstract representation of the exact moments in our lives when something is cut. It could be moving to a different country, being fired, quitting a bad habit, when a relationship ends or when you receive a very bad (or good!) news.
By themselves, cuts are not positive or negative events; it really depends on who you were before and who you wish to be after. But one thing is sure: every cut creates a new space that wasn’t there. This space could be small or huge, ordered or chaotic, regardless, you have to deal with it. Sometimes cuts try to resist and heal themselves extruding the core of the fibres we are made of, but they will fail. A cut is irreversible and it’s up to us to fill the gap with meaning.

Main features include:
- Curated palettes (21)
- Drawing modes (3)
- Extrusions (yes/no)
- Orientation (3)
- Overlapping (yes/no)
- Covered area (2)
- Cut position (2)

In live mode:
- Press [s] to save a 2400x2400 px image
- Press [t] to toggle shading (sometimes flat colours rock!)
- Press [c] to see copyright notice
- Press [f] to log features in console

By Todemashi 2022
NFT License 2.0

### NOTES
Made with p5js and GLSL shaders.
Shaders are based on tutorials and code by Patricio Gonzalez Vivo - The Book of Shaders - https://thebookofshaders.com/

metadata.name: Proxima #324
metadata.description:
The preparations for the first mission began in 2142. It had become clear that mining petroleum on Earth would soon become financially unfeasible, so looking to other planets was the only logical choice. It took seventeen more years to perfect the technology so that the first colonists could reach Proxima b within the lifetime of one generation.

After 45 years of travelling at almost one-tenth of the speed of light, they reached their new home. It was rich in petrochemicals but scarce in the nutrients necessary for long term human survival. After merely six generations, humanity was forced to travel once again in search of a new world. The four missions that parted from the Proxima system to colonise other possibly habitable planets in the galaxy sparked a new age of human civilisation that would never see itself united and thriving again.

Eventually, all the colonies became independent societies as their differing interests drove them apart. Each small civilisation chose its path, wandering the void of space alone. Over time, millions of kilometres apart, each colony developed its own culture and traditions. While their habits and customs changed, some things remained the same across all the societies, like how it became a certain tradition to convert the outer world years and days to Earth time and celebrate holidays according to the calendar of the old world.

The new nomads learned from the first pilgrims. They used the technology once optimised for oil extraction to traverse other worlds, searching for sustenance. Peculiar wandering nonspaces emerged from the involuntary degrowth of human civilisation.

-----

Click on the image to open the menu. You may choose the quality from preview to the resolution of a print of approximately 30cm in height. In live mode, click on PNG to save the rendered image.
Depending on the device and CPU usage, it takes from a few seconds (on fast computers) to a minute (sometimes more) on mid-tier phones to render the image.

Requirements: 1GB of RAM. The system needs up to 200 MB of free RAM for rendering square preview images and up to 400 MB of free RAM for rendering square images at the highest resolution. We tested on Chrome, Safari, Firefox, Edge / Windows, Mac OS, Android, and iPhone, but please make sure it works on your device before minting.

Original piece by mrkswcz and Ismahelio. Made with Three.js. 

San Sebastian - Madrid. May 2022.

metadata.name: Dencity #722
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ❤️, code and p5js.

metadata.name: The Past Ahead #254
metadata.description:
Cyanotypes once were the most advanced technology to create images. When I see one today I look at it as a beautiful relic and I can't help but put my present in perspective. In these uncertain times the technologies we use to create are threatened with sudden extinction. But I feel joy in imagining our works joining the strata of history, a fallen species, the breeding ground of creations to come.

Controls :

• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

The Past Ahead by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity

metadata.name: The Unrealized Painting #50
metadata.description:
Click to start.

The size of the canvas is proportional to the monitor. You can scale up using 1,2,3 and 4 of you keyboard to increase the quality of resolution (it may create some variations on the art itself, and it should be done before clicking on canvas)

The preview is only a sketch of the artwork, since the livecoding functions vary depending on the interaction.

This project was designed in Hydra.js for Desktop computers on Chrome.

Since it is a livecoding library there may be small differences in each code execution, but the deterministic character remains.

The machine waits for your command to start drawing - there is no plan or goal, sometimes the values assigned to the variables would lead to the construction of a visually recognizable work, but the fact that these values are randomized 4 times during the duration of the interaction breaks the logical line of visual conduction.

I can only appeal to Gestalt, and beg you to make the effort to see the whole divided between 4 apparently disconnected patterns. This is not just a code that generates noises, I am here making a testament to push once again the limit of abstraction, to perhaps convince you that there is immense beauty in discontinuity.

And it is worth commenting once again that without your click/command, the machine will be eternally lodged in the server waiting - and not knowing what it is waiting for. And this waiting is the most beautiful thing in the world, because the art is already determined to happen, its strokes and patterns were defined when the hash was tied to the code, the art was already made and already exists in the moment preceding this one - but for a computer time does not exist.

The Unrealized Painting has come to remind you that we, the ones with souls and who feel time, control the realizable and the unrealizable - and it will never stop being that way.
